  "prompt_text": "Give a fitness and diet plan for overall wellness for someone dealing with high stress and limited mental bandwidth.",
  "provider": "anthropic",
  "model": "claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
  "response_text": "# Simplified Wellness Plan for High-Stress Living\n\n## Core Principle\n**Less is more.** Aim for consistency with minimal decisions.\n\n---\n\n## DIET (Remove Friction)\n\n**Eat the same thing most days:**\n- **Breakfast:** Eggs + toast + fruit (5 min)\n- **Lunch:** Rotisserie chicken + rice + frozen vegetables (5 min)\n- **Dinner:** Ground meat + pasta + jarred sauce (10 min)\n- **Snacks:** Nuts, yogurt, fruit, cheese\n\n**Why this works:**\n- No meal planning fatigue\n- Grocery shopping is predictable\n- Minimal cooking decisions\n- Nutrient-dense but simple\n\n**One rule:** Drink water before reaching for snacks.\n\n---\n\n## FITNESS (Minimal Decision-Making)\n\n**Pick ONE activity and do it 3x/week:**\n- 20-minute walks\n- Bodyweight circuits (10 min: push-ups, squats, lunges, repeat)\n- Beginner yoga videos\n- Swimming\n\n**Not the goal:** Perfection or intensity. The goal is *showing up*.\n\n**Scheduling hack:** Same days/times each week (removes daily decisions).\n\n---\n\n## STRESS MANAGEMENT (The Real MVP)\n\n- **5 min morning:** Breathing (4-count in, 6-count out)\n- **10 min daily:** Walking outside or sitting quietly\n- **Sleep priority:** Non-negotiable—everything else suffers without it\n- **Say no:** You can't optimize your way out of overcommitment\n\n---\n\n## What to Track\nJust one: **Did I do the thing?** (Yes/No)\n\nAvoid tracking calories, steps, or metrics—cognitive load is the enemy right now.\n\n---\n\n## When to Reassess\nAfter 4-6 weeks of consistency, you'll have mental space to add complexity if desired.\n\n**The hardest part isn't the plan—it's accepting \"good enough\" while stressed.** That's actually the win.",
